SIMPLE: solicit
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Solicit
<hw>So*lic"it</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Solicited</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Soliciting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>sollicier</ets>, L.
<ets>sollicitare</ets>, <ets>solicitare</ets>, <ets>-atum</ets>, fr.
<ets>sollicitus</ets> wholly (<it>i. e.</it>, violently) moved;
<ets>sollus</ets> whole + <ets>citus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>ciere</ets> to
move, excite. See <er>Solemn</er>, <er>Cite</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To ask from with earnestness; to make petition to; to apply to for
obtaining something; <as>as, to <ex>solicit</ex> person for
alms</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Did I <qex>solicit</qex> thee⟦br⟧
From darkness to promote me?</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To endeavor to obtain; to seek; to plead for;
<as>as, to <ex>solicit</ex> an office; to <ex>solicit</ex> a
favor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I view my crime, but kindle at the view,⟦br⟧
Repent old pleasures, and <qex>solicit</qex> new.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To awake or excite to action; to rouse desire in; to
summon; to appeal to; to invite.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That fruit . . . <qex>solicited</qex> her longing eye.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sounds and some tangible qualities <qex>solicit</qex> their proper
senses, and force an entrance to the mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To urge the claims of; to plead; to act as solicitor
for or with reference to.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Should⟦br⟧
My brother henceforth study to forget⟦br⟧
The vow that he hath made thee, I would ever⟦br⟧
<qex>Solicit</qex> thy deserts.</q> <rj><qau>Ford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To disturb; to disquiet; -- a Latinism rarely
used.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hath any ill <qex>solicited</qex> thine ears?</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But anxious fears <qex>solicit</qex> my weak breast.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> To beseech; ask; request; crave; supplicate;
entreat; beg; implore; importune. See <er>Beseech</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Solicitant</ent>⟦br⟧
